   <sec>
    <title>
     Roles of Arf1 binding sites on β1 and γ in TGN/endosomal localization
    </title>
    <p>
     Having established the presence of two Arf1 recruitment sites
     <em>
      in vitro
     </em>
     , we examined the effect of disrupting the Arf1-binding sites of β1 and γ on the recruitment of these proteins to the TGN/endosomes in whole cells. GFP-tagged forms of β1
     <sup>
      ΔArf1
     </sup>
     and γ
     <sup>
      ΔArf1
     </sup>
     were incorporated into AP-1 complexes as efficiently as their wild-type counterparts when expressed by transfection into cells (
     <xref ref-type="fig">
      Fig. 4A, B
     </xref>
     ), consistent with previous observations (
     <xref ref-type="bibr">
      Farias et al., 2012
     </xref>
     ;
     <xref ref-type="bibr">
      Huang et al., 2001
     </xref>
     ). GFP-tagged β1 (β1
     <sup>
      WT
     </sup>
     -GFP) and mCherry-tagged γ (γ
     <sup>
      WT
     </sup>
